<div id="review_2635205215" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2635205215" />
    <a title="Joshi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/85693689-joshi"><img alt="Joshi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1568151390p2/85693689.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2635205215?book_show_action=true">Apr 26, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joshi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joshi" href="/user/show/85693689-joshi">Joshi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85693689-joshi?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85693689-joshi?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2635205215" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer475023945328977547">Oh my, what a journey. To shortly describe the plot, this book is the tale of two dogs who escape their looming demise at an animal research facility and afterwards try to survive in the wilderness of the Lake District in northern England and by doing so they unintentionally cause quite the uproar. In addition to the two dogs they are joined by a fox and large parts of the book are also written from the point of view of human characters, scientists, journalists, farmers and even politicians all </span>
  <span id="freeText475023945328977547" style="display:none">Oh my, what a journey. To shortly describe the plot, this book is the tale of two dogs who escape their looming demise at an animal research facility and afterwards try to survive in the wilderness of the Lake District in northern England and by doing so they unintentionally cause quite the uproar. In addition to the two dogs they are joined by a fox and large parts of the book are also written from the point of view of human characters, scientists, journalists, farmers and even politicians all the way to the south in London.<br /><br />The chapters from the dogs' point of view are almost always heart breaking. One of them, Snitter, did once have an owner while the other, Rowf, never did. Subsequently, while Snitter wants to find a new owner (as he knows that some people are not bad, Rowf (who never knew anyone other than the scientists experimenting on him) wants nothing more than to get away from them. The experiments conducted on them also add another layer in their interactions: Snitter had undergone brain surgery and trouble in telling dreams and reality apart, often hallucinating. Rowf was part of a sick experiment where he had been placed in a water filled tank again and again to see if he would manage to stay afloat for longer each time, but in his view of what a good dog was supposed to do, he had failed his owners by escaping instead of drowning as they wanted him to.<br /><br />The human characters are great, although some of them are greatly evil more than anything. Really going into more detail on them would spoil too much, but I'll just say that at the end of the book you will have a more positive outlook on some of them...others just remain pure evil. Especially on the last 100 pages or so there are many quite philosophical and 'deep' remarks and discussions by the human characters as the story (quite rapidly I must say) approaches it's end, which I did not expect at all to go down like that.<br /><br />The writing is excellent as I expected after reading Watership Down and I just love Richard Adams style, how he manages to slide in metaphors to the ancient Greek and Roman world and how he writes in general...I can't really describe it, but reading his stories is a joy. On the topic of Richard Adams I'd just like to say that I'd have loved to meet him, he seems like a great man who deeply cared about animals, the environment and the nature of his native England.<br /><br />Overall, I'd say I enjoyed Watership Down a bit more but this book is nonetheless excellent. <br /><br />And I don't know where to put this in this review so I'll say it here: perhaps the saddest thing I'll take from this book isn't any part of the story really but more from the introduction, that all the experiments performed on animals in this book have actually been conducted in the real world.</span>
  <a data-text-id="475023945328977547" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

